I've been here a couple time for beers and it's a solid bar. Prices are great for the area with a couple decent beers for only $5. Recently I went to grab some food, I had heard they had a great burger and wanted to check it out. We started with the fried mac and cheese. I've never been impressed with fried mac and cheese and this did nothing to change my mind. I also though the sriracha ketchup was a terrible accompaniment. I went with a double burger with bacon for my main. It reminded me of a slightly fancier more dolled up shake shack burger. It was a solid burger but nothing worth going out of your way for, the fries were pretty decent as well. Service wasn't great but wasn't bad, the waiter forgot one of the beer and ended up comping it which was nice. There are board games and shuffleboard which is a plus, it's definitely a solid bar to go with friends to grab a drink.

I really love Dram Shop but a $25 minimum is ridiculous. When the ATM that you have outside of your shop is BROKEN and doesn't work, sending someone outside of the bar to get cash is ridiculous.  I've always understood that anything more than a $10 minimum is not technically legal.  This is just bad business. If the ATM is broken, your servers should really find a way to make a customer feel as though something has been done for them and not send them to CVS to get cash. I mean it's just bad business and really poor customer service. You should have made an exception.  I'm not convinced I'll return. Our waitress should have run the bill and dealt with it.

Dram Shop is one of the better Irish pubs I've been to in Brooklyn.  Really it's just a great neighborhood bar.  It's very narrow with the bar taking up the majority of the right side.  Bartenders can be a little swamped sometimes but they've always been friendly.  Beer selection is above average for an Irish pub given that it's located in craft beer-heavy Park Slope; nothing heavy duty but you can reliable beers like Bell's Two Hearted fresh.  The place packs out for big sports games but that adds to the atmosphere; people tend to be very friendly here so I consider that a plus.  People rave about the burger here, but I'm fond of the chili.  It is thick, meaty, and spicy without being overwhelmingly so.  The Fritos that come with it are clutch, allowing you to make your own Frito pie if you wish (this is a massive plus with me).  The crackers that come with it too just confuse me.  Either way, it is serious chili even if it doesn't include beans.  People speak well of the food here across the board, and it's especially awesome  that it's also available late (came here once for food at 2am).  Generally Dram Shop is a good all purpose bar that you'll wish you had in your neighborhood.

The place doesn't really "get" how to be a sports bar on Sundays.  There are some crappy sight lines, they don't honor teams "spot" in the bar (when the Packers are playing the Bears, don't move the Packers fans to our TV, you're just inviting trouble).  The food is decent, but not great.  The burger is fine, but probably overrated.  The fries are pretty good, don't bother with the "Irish nachos" style.  The wings are in the neighborhood of average, but overpriced.  The tostadas aren't very good, and also overpriced.  Happy hour beer specials are very good though, and they have a fine selection of beers on tap.  The service is also good, save the random times when the bartender accidentally changes the channel of the game you're watching.
